      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy for Dance Words</h2>
      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors"><p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">WALTZ is the best 5-letter Z word:</span> At 3.4 points per tile, WALTZ outscores longer Z words for efficiency. W=4 and Z=10 do all the work while A, L, T are common fillers you'll almost always have available.</p></div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors"><p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">JIVE clears J+V together:</span> J (8pts) and V (4pts) are both awkward tiles. JIVE uses both in one 4-letter word for 14 points. That's two problem tiles solved simultaneously with minimal rack commitment.</p></div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors"><p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Dance words hook well:</span> WALTZ→WALTZED, JIVE→JIVED/JIVES, POLKA→POLKAS, TANGO→TANGOS. Most dance names take standard English suffixes, giving you extension options on future turns.</p></div>
